{"title_page": "Forgive and Forget (2000 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Forgive and Forget\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| alt            =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Aisling Walsh]]\n| producer       = Philip Hinchclif, Carmel Meloney, Simon Passmore\n| writer         = Mark Burt\n| starring       = [[John Simm]]<br>[[Steve John Shepherd]]<br>[[Laura Fraser]]<br>[[Maurice Ro\u00ebves]]\n| music          = Hal Lindes\n| cinematography = Kevin Rowley\n| editing        = Chris Bucland\n| studio         = [[Scottish Television Enterprises]]\n| released       = {{filmdate|2000|1|3|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 100 minutes\n| country        = [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| language       = [[English language|English]]\n}}\n\n'''''Forgive and Forget''''' is a 2000 British [[made-for-television]] film in which a young latent gay man confronts his sexuality and increasing jealousy when his best friend moves in with his new girlfriend. The film was broadcast on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] on 3 January 2000.\n\n==Plot==\nThe close friendship between plasterer David ([[Steve John Shepherd]]) and mature-aged student Theo ([[John Simm]]) becomes threatened when Theo reveals that he intends to move in with Hannah ([[Laura Fraser]]), his photographer girlfriend of six months. The short-tempered David, intensely protective of his best friend, plots to break the pair up, using Hannah's insecurities against them. When they do separate, David reveals his sexual  orientation and true feelings for Theo on his favourite talk-show, Judith Adams' ([[Meera Syal]]) ''Forgive and Forget''.<ref>\u2018Forgive and Forget (2000 TV Movie)\u2019, \u201cInternet Movie Database\u2019\u2019 [website], <[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0229397/]>, accessed 31 August 2015.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{Castlist|\n*[[John Simm]] as Theo\n*[[Steve John Shepherd]] as David O'Neil\n*[[Laura Fraser]] as Hannah\n*[[Maurice Ro\u00ebves]] as Michael O'Neil\n*[[Ger Ryan]] as Ruth O'Neil\n*[[Meera Syal]] as Judith Adams\n*[[Stephen Graham]] as John\n*Roger Griffiths as Carlton\n* Huggy Leaver as Paul\n*Charles De\u2019Ath (credited as Charlie De'Ath) as Alex\n*Isabella Marsh as Gabby\n*[[Jonathan Slinger]] as Carl\n*Nikki Amuka-Bird as Nicky\n*Annette Bentley as Michelle\n*June Page as Carol\n*Paul Panting as Gerry\n*Jenny Paterson as Caroline\n*Jack Pierce \tas John\n*Sam Rumbelow as 1st Man in Bar\n*Ash Logan as 2nd Man in Bar\n*Nicola Sanderson as Jackie\n*Cameron Williams as Gary\n*Thomas Jamerson \tas Homeless Man\n}}\n\n==Reception==\nWriting for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', Dennis Harvey has mixed feeling about the script, praising Mark Burt's balance of \u2018the primary character trio\u2019s unremarkable yet complex emotions, framing them in well-captured pub/construction site/family milieus.\u2019 But felt that the \u2018somewhat gratuitous running gag\u2014glimpses of the titular, fictional chat show, a kinder-gentler ''[[The Jerry Springer Show|Jerry Springer]]''-type mix of real folks and hot-button topics\u2014suddenly takes center stage.\u2019 He added that this \u2018good little movie abruptly grows loud, large and heavy-handed in the last reel.\u2019 Harvey praised the acting saying that \u2018there\u2019s much to enjoy here, particularly in the uniformly fine cast. \u2026 Shepherd \u2026 is a real find, convincingly rendering David as withdrawn, laddish and lovesick all at once. Apart from some killing-time interludes set to pop tunes, and the rather cheesy flash of horizontal-wipe scene transitions, helmer Aisling Walsh lends material both youthful breeziness and emotional weight.\u2019<ref>Dennis Harvey, \u2018Review: \u2018Forgive and Forget\u2019\u2019, \u201cVariety\u2019\u2019 [website], <[https://variety.com/2000/film/reviews/forgive-and-forget-1200463422/]>, accessed 1 September 2015.</ref>\n\n''Filmcritic.com''\u2019s Christopher Null dismissed the film, declaring that if \u2018you manage to stay interested, well, you're a stouter fellow than I.\u2019<ref>\u2018Forgive and Forget\u2019\u2019, \u201cRotten Tomatoes\u2019\u2019 [website], <[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/forgive_and_forget/]>, accessed 1 September 2015.</ref>\n\n''TV Guide''\u2019s Troy Lambert wrote that despite \u2018the reality-challenged script, director Aisling Walsh delivers decent performances from the cast, especially Shepherd, Simm and Fraser as the unlikely three-way.\u2019<ref>\u2018Forgive and Forget\u2019\u2019, \u201cTV Guide\u2019\u2019 [website], <[http://www.tvguide.com/movies/forgive-and-forget/review/135400/]>, accessed 1 September 2015.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Aisling Walsh}}\n[[Category:2000s drama films]]\n[[Category:British LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:British television films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related drama films]]\n[[Category:2000s LGBT-related films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Forgive and Forget\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| alt            =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Aisling Walsh]]\n| producer       = Philip Hinchclif, Carmel Meloney, Simon Passmore\n| writer         = Mark Burt\n| starring       = [[John Simm]]<br>[[Steve John Shepherd]]<br>[[Laura Fraser]]<br>[[Maurice Ro\u00ebves]]\n| music          = Hal Lindes\n| cinematography = Kevin Rowley\n| editing        = Chris Bucland\n| studio         = [[Scottish Television Enterprises]]\n| released       = {{filmdate|2000|1|3|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 100 minutes\n| country        = [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| language       = [[English language|English]]\n}}\n\n'''''Forgive and Forget''''' is a 2000 British [[made-for-television]] film in which a young latent gay man confronts his sexuality and increasing jealousy when his best friend moves in with his new girlfriend. The film was broadcast on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] on 3 January 2000.\n\n==Plot==\nThe close friendship between plasterer David ([[Steve John Shepherd]]) and mature-aged student Theo ([[John Simm]]) becomes threatened when Theo reveals that he intends to move in with Hannah ([[Laura Fraser]]), his photographer girlfriend of six months. The short-tempered David, intensely protective of his best friend, plots to break the pair up, using Hannah\u2019s insecurities against them. When they do separate, David reveals his sexual  orientation and true feelings for Theo on his favourite talk-show, Judith Adams' ([[Meera Syal]]) ''Forgive and Forget''.<ref>\u2018Forgive and Forget (2000 TV Movie)\u2019, \u201cInternet Movie Database\u2019\u2019 [website], <[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0229397/]>, accessed 31 August 2015.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{Castlist|\n*[[John Simm]] as Theo\n*[[Steve John Shepherd]] as David O'Neil\n*[[Laura Fraser]] as Hannah\n*[[Maurice Ro\u00ebves]] as Michael O'Neil\n*[[Ger Ryan]] as Ruth O'Neil\n*[[Meera Syal]] as Judith Adams\n*[[Stephen Graham]] as John\n*Roger Griffiths as Carlton\n* Huggy Leaver as Paul\n*Charles De\u2019Ath (credited as Charlie De'Ath) as Alex\n*Isabella Marsh as Gabby\n*[[Jonathan Slinger]] as Carl\n*Nikki Amuka-Bird as Nicky\n*Annette Bentley as Michelle\n*June Page as Carol\n*Paul Panting as Gerry\n*Jenny Paterson as Caroline\n*Jack Pierce \tas John\n*Sam Rumbelow as 1st Man in Bar\n*Ash Logan as 2nd Man in Bar\n*Nicola Sanderson as Jackie\n*Cameron Williams as Gary\n*Thomas Jamerson \tas Homeless Man\n}}\n\n==Reception==\nWriting for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', Dennis Harvey has mixed feeling about the script, praising Mark Burt\u2019s balance of \u2018the primary character trio\u2019s unremarkable yet complex emotions, framing them in well-captured pub/construction site/family milieus.\u2019 But felt that the \u2018somewhat gratuitous running gag\u2014glimpses of the titular, fictional chat show, a kinder-gentler ''[[The Jerry Springer Show|Jerry Springer]]''-type mix of real folks and hot-button topics\u2014suddenly takes center stage.\u2019 He added that this \u2018good little movie abruptly grows loud, large and heavy-handed in the last reel.\u2019 Harvey praised the acting saying that \u2018there\u2019s much to enjoy here, particularly in the uniformly fine cast. \u2026 Shepherd \u2026 is a real find, convincingly rendering David as withdrawn, laddish and lovesick all at once. Apart from some killing-time interludes set to pop tunes, and the rather cheesy flash of horizontal-wipe scene transitions, helmer Aisling Walsh lends material both youthful breeziness and emotional weight.\u2019<ref>Dennis Harvey, \u2018Review: \u2018Forgive and Forget\u2019\u2019, \u201cVariety\u2019\u2019 [website], <[https://variety.com/2000/film/reviews/forgive-and-forget-1200463422/]>, accessed 1 September 2015.</ref>\n\n''Filmcritic.com''\u2019s Christopher Null dismissed the film, declaring that if \u2018you manage to stay interested, well, you're a stouter fellow than I.\u2019<ref>\u2018Forgive and Forget\u2019\u2019, \u201cRotten Tomatoes\u2019\u2019 [website], <[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/forgive_and_forget/]>, accessed 1 September 2015.</ref>\n\n''TV Guide''\u2019s Troy Lambert wrote that despite \u2018the reality-challenged script, director Aisling Walsh delivers decent performances from the cast, especially Shepherd, Simm and Fraser as the unlikely three-way.\u2019<ref>\u2018Forgive and Forget\u2019\u2019, \u201cTV Guide\u2019\u2019 [website], <[http://www.tvguide.com/movies/forgive-and-forget/review/135400/]>, accessed 1 September 2015.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Aisling Walsh}}\n[[Category:2000s drama films]]\n[[Category:British LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:British television films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related drama films]]\n[[Category:2000s LGBT-related films]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forgive_and_Forget_(2000_film)"}
{"title_page": "Downton Abbey (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|Historical drama film directed by Michael Engler}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Downton Abbey\n| image = DowntonAbbey2019Poster.jpg\n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Michael Engler]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Julian Fellowes]]\n* [[Gareth Neame]]\n* Liz Trubridge\n}}\n| screenplay = Julian Fellowes\n| based on = {{Based on|''[[Downton Abbey]]''|Julian Fellowes}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Hugh Bonneville]]\n* [[Jim Carter (actor)|Jim Carter]]\n* [[Michelle Dockery]]\n* [[Elizabeth McGovern]]\n* [[Maggie Smith]]\n* [[Imelda Staunton]]\n* [[Penelope Wilton]]\n}}\n| music = [[John Lunn]]\n| cinematography = Ben Smithard\n| editing = [[Mark Day (editor)|Mark Day]]\n| studio = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Perfect World Pictures]]\n* [[Focus Features]]\n* [[Carnival Films]]<ref name=\"Distributor\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/downton-abbey-movie-gets-go-ahead-with-series-cast-returning-1202872674/|title='Downton Abbey' Movie Officially a Go With Series Cast Returning|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=13 July 2018|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| distributor = {{unbulleted list|[[Universal Pictures UK]] (United Kingdom)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/downton-abbey-film|title=DOWNTON ABBEY &#124; British Board of Film Classification|website=bbfc.co.uk}}</ref>|Focus Features (United States)}}\n| released = {{Film date|df=yes|2019|9|9|[[Leicester Square]]|2019|9|13|United Kingdom|2019|9|20|United States}}\n| runtime = 122 minutes\n| country =  {{unbulleted list|United Kingdom|United States}}\n| language = English\n| budget = $13\u201320 million<ref name=\"WrapBudget\" /><ref name=\"opening\" />\n| gross = $194 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|title= Downton Abbey (2019)|url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=downtonabbey.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NUM\">{{cite web|title=Downton Abbey (2019)|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Downton-Abbey-(UK)-(2019)#tab=summary|website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Downton Abbey''''' is a 2019 [[historical drama film]] written by [[Julian Fellowes]], creator and writer of the [[Downton Abbey|television series of the same name]],<ref name=\"urlJulian Fellowes List of Movies and TV Shows|TV Guide\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/julian-fellowes/credits/159291/#33e34403ada425d45e7ed27b1f23849f|title=Julian Fellowes List of Movies and TV Shows &#124; TV Guide|publisher= CBS Interactive Inc.|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref> produced by [[Gareth Neame]], Liz Trubridge and Fellowes, and directed by [[Michael Engler]]. The film is a [[Carnival Films]] production, with [[Focus Features]] and Universal Pictures International distributing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.focusfeatures.com/article/production-announcement_downton-abbey-movie|title=Focus Features Announces Production on the Downton Abbey Movie|website=Focus Features|language=en|access-date=22 September 2019}}</ref> and continues the storyline from the series, with much of the original cast returning.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/film/2018-12-23/downton-abbey-bosses-reveal-why-they-didnt-bring-back-lily-james-for-the-movie/|title=Downton Abbey bosses reveal why they didn't bring back Lily James for the movie|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=23 December 2018|accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref> The film, set in 1927, depicts a visit by the King and Queen to the Crawley family's [[English country house]] in the Yorkshire countryside. As the Royal staff descend on Downton, an assassin has also arrived and attempts to kill the monarch. The family and servants are pitted against the royal entourage, including the Queen's [[lady-in-waiting]], who has fallen out with the Crawleys, especially the Dowager Countess, over an inheritance issue.\n\n[[Gareth Neame]] and Fellowes started planning a feature adaptation in 2016, shortly after the series ended. It was officially confirmed in July 2018 and filming began later that month, lasting through November. The film was released in the United Kingdom on 13 September 2019, and in the United States on 20 September 2019. It received generally positive reviews from critics and grossed $192 million worldwide.\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1927, about a year and a half after the TV series ended. [[Buckingham Palace]] informs Robert and Cora Crawley, the Earl and Countess of Grantham, that [[George V|King George V]] and [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]] will visit Downton Abbey during a royal tour through [[Yorkshire]]. Violet Crawley, Dowager Countess of Grantham, is perturbed that Maud, Lady Bagshaw, Queen Mary's lady-in-waiting, is included in the tour. Robert is Maud's cousin and closest relative, and the two families have long disputed who should inherit Maud's estate.\n\nThe [[Royal Households of the United Kingdom|royal household staff]] arrive, including Mr Wilson, the Royal [[Page of the Backstairs]]; Mrs Webb, the Royal Housekeeper; Miss Lawton, the Queen's Royal Dresser; Monsieur Courbet, the Royal Chef; and Richard Ellis, the King's Royal Dresser. All but Ellis are dismissive and arrogant to the Downton servants. Upstairs, eldest Crawley daughter Lady Mary Talbot, the estate manager, constantly worries about keeping Downton afloat in a fast-changing world. Believing Mr Barrow cannot manage a royal visit, Mary asks Mr Carson, Downton's retired butler, to temporarily resume his duties. Barrow, strongly protesting, steps aside.\n\nMajor Chetwode arrives in Downton Village seeking out the Granthams' Irish son-in-law, Tom Branson. Tom assumes Chetwode is a detective assessing security for the royal visit. Prior to the royal parade starting through Downton Village, Chetwode stations himself near where the King is awaiting the Royal Artillery, unaware that Tom has grown suspicious. As Chetwode aims a pistol at King George, Tom tackles Chetwode, pinning him to the ground. The real royal detectives apprehend Chetwode, an Irish Republican sympathizer who erroneously believed Tom was an ally.\n\nThe royal entourage has completely displaced the Downton household. Meanwhile, Tom and Lucy Smith, Lady Maud's maid, form a mutual attraction. Bertie and Edith Pelham, the Marquess and Marchioness of Hexham, also arrive at Downton. The King asks Bertie to accompany the [[Edward VIII|Prince of Wales]] on a three-month African tour. The news distresses Edith, the younger Crawley daughter, who tells Bertie she is pregnant and is due just as Bertie would depart. In the garden, Tom encounters a sobbing woman, unaware she is [[Mary, Princess Royal and Countess of Harewood|Princess Mary]]. He initiates a conversation which inspires the Princess to remain with her [[Henry Lascelles, 6th Earl of Harewood|husband]]. Meanwhile, Anna discovers Miss Lawton is stealing small objects from Downton Abbey. She demands their return, then blackmails Lawton into [[dress fitting|altering]] an over-sized ballgown to fit Lady Edith after the wrong dress was mistakenly delivered to Downton.\n\nAnna and John Bates unite the staff into retaking control downstairs to defend Downton's honour. Barrow and Mr Ellis trick some royal household staff into returning to London. Anna slips a strong sleeping aid into Courbet's tea, and Mr Wilson is \"accidentally\" locked inside his room, allowing Mrs Patmore and Daisy to cook the dinner, and Mr Carson and the Downton footmen to wait at table. When the King praises the revised menu, Molesley impulsively blurts out that the Downton staff prepared the meal and are serving it. Robert apologises for Molesley's inappropriate outburst, but the Queen says they are accustomed to people behaving strangely around them.\n\nThat same evening, Barrow and Ellis go to [[York]]. While Ellis visits his parents, Barrow waits at a local pub. A man there invites Barrow to a hidden gay nightclub. Shortly after Barrow arrives, police raid the club. Ellis, who is secretly gay, discovers what happened and uses his royal connection to secure Barrow's release. Afterwards, the two men develop a bond, indicating they will meet again.\n\nBack at Downton, as the inheritance conflict escalates, Isobel, Lady Merton, surmises correctly that Lucy is Maud's secret illegitimate daughter, which is the reason she is Maud's heir. She tells Maud she must inform Violet. The next morning, assistant cook Daisy, who doubted if footman Andy was the right man for her, realizes she does love him and begins planning their wedding. Henry Talbot, Mary's husband, returns from abroad in time to accompany the family to [[Harewood House]] with the royal party.\n\nDuring the ball at Harewood, Princess Mary informs her parents that Tom inspired her to save her marriage, prompting the King to personally thank him. Also, the Queen has persuaded the King to release Bertie from the imminent tour. Maud tells Violet about Lucy. Violet does not approve but understands, and immediately schemes to unite the two households through Lucy and Tom when told they plan to write to one another. Mary privately queries her grandmother regarding her recent trip to [[London]]. Violet confides that medical tests reveal she may die soon, but she assures a distraught Mary that Downton's legacy is safe in her hands. Tom later seeks out Lucy on the terrace and dances with her.\n\nMr Carson and Mrs Hughes ponder Downton's future in the modern era. Carson asserts it will stand for another hundred years with the Crawley family still in residence.\n\n==Cast==\n{{see also|List of Downton Abbey characters}}\n{{cast list|\n* [[Hugh Bonneville]] as Robert Crawley, 7th Earl of Grantham\n* [[Laura Carmichael]] as Edith Pelham (n\u00e9e Crawley), Marchioness of Hexham\n* [[Jim Carter (actor)|Jim Carter]] as Charles Carson\n* [[Raquel Cassidy]] as Phyllis Baxter\n* [[Brendan Coyle]] as John Bates\n* [[Michelle Dockery]] as Lady Mary Talbot (n\u00e9e Crawley)\n* [[Kevin Doyle (actor)|Kevin Doyle]] as Joseph Molesley\n* [[Michael C. Fox]] as Andy Parker\n* [[Joanne Froggatt]] as Anna Bates\n* [[Matthew Goode]] as Henry Talbot\n* [[Harry Hadden-Paton]] as Bertie Pelham, 7th Marquess of Hexham\n* [[Robert James-Collier]] as Thomas Barrow\n* [[Allen Leech]] as Tom Branson\n* [[Phyllis Logan]] as Elsie Hughes\n* [[Elizabeth McGovern]] as Cora Crawley, Countess of Grantham\n* [[Sophie McShera]] as Daisy Mason\n* [[Lesley Nicol (actress)|Lesley Nicol]] as Beryl Patmore\n* [[Maggie Smith]] as Violet Crawley, Dowager Countess of Grantham\n* [[Imelda Staunton]] as Maud, Lady Bagshaw\n* [[Penelope Wilton]] as Isobel, Lady Merton\n* [[Mark Addy]] as Mr Bakewell\n* [[Max Brown (actor)|Max Brown]] as Richard Ellis\n* [[Stephen Campbell Moore]] as Major Chetwode\n* [[Richenda Carey]] as Mrs Webb\n* [[David Haig]] as Mr Wilson\n* [[Andrew Havill]] as [[Henry Lascelles, 6th Earl of Harewood|Henry, Viscount Lascelles]]\n* [[Geraldine James]] as [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]]\n* [[Simon Jones (actor)|Simon Jones]] as [[George V|King George V]]\n* [[Susan Lynch]] as Miss Lawton\n* [[Tuppence Middleton]] as Lucy Smith\n* [[Kate Phillips (British actress)|Kate Phillips]] as [[Mary, Princess Royal and Countess of Harewood|The Princess Mary, Viscountess Lascelles]]\n* James Cartwright as Tony Sellick\n* Douglas Reith as Richard, Lord Merton\n* Philippe Spall as Monsieur Courbet\n* Oliver and Zac Barker as Master George\n* Fifi Hart as Miss Sybbie\n* Eva and Karina Samms as Miss Marigold\n}}\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Highclere Castle (April 2011).jpg|thumb|right|[[Highclere Castle]], the site used as the fictional Downton Abbey estate.]]\n===Development===\nThe original television series, ''Downton Abbey'', ended in 2015, after 52 episodes<ref name=\"HowardBianculli2018\">{{cite book|author1=Douglas L. Howard|author2=David Bianculli|title=Television Finales: From Howdy Doody to Girls|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5nN0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA105|date=13 November 2018|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=978-0-8156-5447-6|page=105}}</ref><ref name=\"url'Downton Abbey' Series Finale Recap: The End of An Era \u2013 Variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/downton-abbey-series-finale-recap-1201706224/|title='Downton Abbey' Series Finale Recap: The End of An Era \u2013 Variety|author= Debra Birnbaum|date= 6 March 2016|publisher= Variety Media, LLC, a subsidiary of Penske Business Media, LLC.|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ceciliarodriguez/2018/07/15/downton-abbey-is-returning-with-the-original-cast-to-the-movies/#3289ab44863c|title=Downton Abbey Is Returning, With The Original Cast, To The Movies|publisher=[[Forbes]]|work=forbes.com|date=15 July 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref> with its final episode set at New Year's Eve, 1925.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Picturehouse Cinemas Ltd.|date=2019|title=Coming Soon: Downton Abbey|journal=Picturehouse Recommends|volume=May/June/July|pages=6}}</ref> In April 2016, it was revealed that a [[film adaptation]] was being considered,<ref>{{cite news|work=The Telegraph|date= 10 April 2016|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2016/04/10/downton-creator-julian-fellowes-why-the-personal-attacks-hurt-so/|title=Downton creator Julian Fellowes: 'Why the personal attacks hurt so much'|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref> with [[Julian Fellowes]] working on an outline plot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/entertainment-arts-36049641/julian-fellowes-i-m-plotting-downton-abbey-film|title=Julian Fellowes: I'm plotting Downton Abbey film|publisher=[[BBC News]]|work=bbc.co.uk/news|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref> A script was distributed to original cast members early in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-39326666|title=Downton Abbey movie 'could be filmed this year'|publisher=[[BBC News]]|work=bbc.co.uk/news|date=20 March 2017|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2018-08-12/downton-abbeys-phyllis-logan-reveals-production-on-the-movie-begins-any-minute-now/|title=Downton Abbey's Phyllis Logan reveals production on the movie begins 'any minute now'|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|work=[[Radio times]]|date=12 August 2018|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 July 2018, the producers confirmed that a feature-length film would be made,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-44822420|title=Downton Abbey film (finally) confirmed|publisher=[[BBC News]]|work=bbc.co.uk/news|date=13 July 2018|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref> with production commencing mid-2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jul/13/downton-abbey-film-confirmed-to-shoot-this-summer-with-series-cast-returning|title=Downton Abbey film confirmed to shoot this summer with series cast returning|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=13 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"forbes\"/> The script was written by Fellowes. The producers are [[Gareth Neame]], Liz Trubridge and Fellowes.<ref name=\"vanityfair.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/07/downton-abbey-movie-cast-summer/|title=It's Happening: Downton Abbey's Original Cast Is Reuniting for a Movie|first=Yohana|last=Desta|publisher=Vanity Fair}}</ref> The film is distributed by [[Focus Features]] and [[Universal Pictures International]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/13/movies/downton-abbey-movie.html|title='Downton Abbey' Movie Is on the Way|work=The New York Times|date=13 July 2018|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref> In late August 2018, it was reported that [[Brian Percival]] had stepped down as director and [[Michael Engler]] took on this job. Percival, in addition to Nigel Marchant, would be an executive producer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/downton-abbey-movie-filming/|title='Downton Abbey' Movie Due to Begin Filming as Cast Grows, Director Replaced|date=31 August 2018|publisher=Collider}}</ref><ref name=\"variety.com\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/imelda-staunton-geraldine-james-downton-abbey-movie-1202922680/|title=Imelda Staunton, Geraldine James Join 'Downton Abbey' Movie|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=30 August 2018|publisher=Variety}}</ref>\n\nThe plot of the film is based on an actual trip by the British royals to [[Wentworth Woodhouse]] in 1912 in order to demonstrate the importance of the monarchy. The estate itself was used as part of the shooting locations because of the story's link to that history.<ref name=\"New Era for the Household\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/when-does-the-downton-abbey-movie-take-place-its-a-new-era-for-the-household-18724874|title=When Does The 'Downton Abbey' Movie Take Place? It's A New Era for the Household|author= Jasmine Ting|date= 16 September 2019|publisher= BUSTLE|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nOriginal cast members including Hugh Bonneville, Elizabeth McGovern, Michelle Dockery, Laura Carmichael and Maggie Smith, were confirmed to return as their characters from the series,<ref name=\"vanityfair.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/maggie-smith-83-to-be-in-downton-abbey-movie/|title=Maggie Smith, 83, to Return for&nbsp;Downton Abbey Big Screen Movie Alongside TV Show's Main Cast|publisher=People.com}}</ref> with Joanne Froggatt confirming her involvement in a separate announcement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.accessonline.com/articles/downton-abbey-movie-coming-and-joanne-froggatt-and-michelle-dockery-are-beyond-excited-about-it/|title=A 'Downton Abbey' Movie Is Coming and Joanne Froggatt and Michelle Dockery Are Beyond Excited About It|publisher=[[KNBC]]|work=[[Access (American TV program)|Access]]|date=13 July 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref> [[Lily James]], who played Lady Rose MacClare, stated she would not be reprising her role for the film,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/lily-james-not-returning-downton-abbey-movie/|title=Lily James Reveals Why There's 'No Space' for Her in Downton Abbey Movie|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=15 July 2018|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2018/07/16/lily-james-will-not-returning-downton-abbey-movie/|title=Lily James will not be returning for the Downton Abbey movie|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=16 July 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018|last1=Corrodus|first1=Corrine}}</ref> as did [[Ed Speleers]] who played footman Jimmy Kent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/downton-abbey/news/a870372/downton-abbey-ed-speleers-not-returning-movie/|title=Downton Abbey star Ed Speleers won't be returning for the film|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=11 November 2018|accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn August 2018 announcement indicated that newcomers Imelda Staunton, Geraldine James, Tuppence Middleton, Simon Jones, David Haig, Kate Phillips, and Stephen Campbell Moore would be among the cast of the film.<ref name=\"variety.com\"/> The producers told the news media that Simon Jones and Geraldine James play the King and Queen, respectively (although not shown in the trailer), while David Haig appears as the King's butler.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.journalpost.com/entertainment/celeb/downton-abbey-is-back-with-an-all-new-movie-trailer/|title='Downton Abbey' is back with an all-new movie trailer|newspaper=Journal Post|date=24 May 2019|access-date=26 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, it was confirmed that Matthew Goode, who played Lady Mary's husband Henry Talbot in the final series, appears only briefly due to other commitments,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-09-03/downton-abbey-movie-matthew-goode-cast-confirmed/|title=Matthew Goode confirmed for Downton Abbey movie&nbsp;\u2013 but he says he will only be \"popping in at the end\"|work=[[Radio Times]]}}</ref> while Jim Carter, Brendan Coyle, Kevin Doyle, Harry Hadden-Paton, Rob James-Collier, Allen Leech, Phyllis Logan, Sophie McShera, Lesley Nicol and Penelope Wilton were confirmed to be reprising their respective roles, with Max Brown joining in a new, undisclosed role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/downton-abbey-movie-sets-fall-2019-opening-1202467698/|title='Downton Abbey' Movie Sets Fall 2019 Opening|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=19 September 2018|publisher=Deadline Hollywood}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/downton-abbey-movie-cast-max-brown-the-royals-1202472427/|title='Downton Abbey' Movie Adds 'The Royals' Max Brown|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=27 September 2018|publisher=Deadline Hollywood}}</ref>\n\n===Costumes===\nCostumes were designed by Anna Mary Scott Robbins working with John Bright of the costume company COSPROP in London, which specializes in historic, period costumes.<ref name=\"Scott Robbins COSPROP\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/09/13/downton-abbey-movie-costumes/|title=Diamonds! Vintage gowns! Inside the Downton Abbey movie costumes fit for a queen|author= Rosy Cordero|date= 13 September 2019|publisher= Meredith Corporation|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref> The company has some of Queen Mary's real wardrobe, studied for details of construction.<ref name=\"Scott Robbins COSPROP\" /> Geraldine James' Queen Mary costume was constructed using material from one of the Queen's actual dresses.<ref name=\"Scott Robbins COSPROP\" /> During the Ball scene, both Michelle Dockery and Elizabeth McGovern wore vintage dresses that were embellished with additional work. Dockery's beaded French gown had beads lengthened to the floor by hand. While Michelle Dockery wears [[Swarovski crystals]] in her tiara, Maggie Smith's is a 19th-century platinum piece<ref name=\"Scott Robbins COSPROP\" /> from Bentley & Skinner of Piccadilly jewellers by Royal appointment<ref name=\"Bentley & Skinner\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bentley-skinner.co.uk/|title=Welcome to Bentley & Skinner \u2013 Bentley & Skinner, the Mayfair antique and bespoke jewellery shop in the heart of London|publisher= Bentley & Skinner (Bond Street Jewellers) Ltd|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref> with 16.5 carats of diamonds. Smith's ball gown was found in a vintage shop in Paris and dye was used to alter the turquoise color to lilac.<ref name=\"Scott Robbins COSPROP\" />\n\n===Filming===\nPrincipal photography started in London in late August 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2456786/the-downton-abbey-movie-has-officially-started-filming|title=The Downton Abbey Movie Has Officially Started Filming|publisher=Gateway Blend|work=Cinemablend|date=1 September 2018|accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"variety.com\"/> By 20 September, some filming was under way at [[Highclere Castle]], Hampshire, which had been the main location for the television series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/movies/downton-abbey-movie-first-images-of-the-lavish-country-set-are-unveiled-as-filming-on-the-eagerly-anticipated-film-gets-underway-at-highclere-castle/ar-BBNALEo|title=Downton Abbey movie: FIRST images of the lavish country set are unveiled as filming on the eagerly anticipated film gets underway at Highclere Castle|publisher=[[MSN]]|work=MSN Entertainment|date=20 September 2018|accessdate=25 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highclerecastle.co.uk/downton-abbey-movie-confirmed|title=DOWNTON ABBEY MOVIE CONFIRMED|publisher=[[Highclere Castle]]|work=express.co.uk|date=5 August 2018|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref> Also in September, filming was under way in [[Lacock]], [[Wiltshire]], with Dame Maggie Smith, Hugh Bonneville, Elizabeth McGovern and Michelle Dockery as well as two new cast members, Imelda Staunton (wife of Jim Carter) and Geraldine James; scenes shot in Lacock included a celebration with horses from the [[Royal Artillery]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gazetteandherald.co.uk/news/16952909.lacock-transformed-for-downton-movie-filming/|title=Downton stars return to Lacock for movie filming|last=Moore|first=Joanne|date=1 October 2018|website=The Wiltshire Gazette and Herald|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=15 December 2018}}</ref> Exterior scenes set in York were filmed on location at [[Beamish Museum]], complete with operational [[tram]]s.<ref name=\"beamish\">{{cite web|title=New Downton Abbey Film at Beamish Museum|url=http://www.beamish.org.uk/news/new-downton-abbey-film-at-beamish-museum/|website=Beamish|accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref> The Heritage Railways scenes were filmed on the North Yorkshire Moors Railway with Pickering terminus representing Kings Cross. The Royal Mail Sorting Office Coach was borrowed from the Great Central Railway at Loughborough. Filming concluded in November 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/allen-leech-interview-bohemian-rhapsody-downton-abbey-movie/|title=Allen Leech on Making 'Bohemian Rhapsody' and the 'Downton Abbey' Movie|work=Collider|publisher=Collider|date=8 November 2018|accessdate=9 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name = Downton Abbey\n| type = soundtrack\n| artist = [[John Lunn]]\n| released = September 13, 2019\n| recorded = 2019\n| genre = [[Soundtrack album]]<br>[[Film score]]\n| length = 53:07\n| label = [[Decca Gold]]<br>[[Decca Records]]<br> [[Universal Music Group#Toronto|Universal Music Canada]]\n| producer = [[John Lunn]]\n}}\n'''''Downton Abbey''''' is the film's soundtrack album and musical score album of the same name, composed by [[John Lunn]], conducted and orchestrated by Alastair King, edited by Mark Willsher and performed by [[London Chamber Orchestra|The Chamber Orchestra of London]] with additional music composed by [[Chris Egan (musician)|Chris Egan]] and prepared by Tristan Noon, while the music for the film's trailer was composed by David James Rosen. It was released on September 13, 2019 on CD, digital download and vinyl by [[Decca Gold]], [[Decca Records]] and [[Universal Music Group#Toronto|Universal Music Canada]].\n\n===Track listing===\n{{Track listing\n| all_music = [[John Lunn]]\n| total_length = 53:07\n| title1 = A Royal Command\n| length1 = 4:49\n| title2 = Pillar of the Establishment\n| length2 = 1:48\n| title3 = Gleam and Sparkle\n| length3 = 2:48\n| title4 = God Is a Monarchist\n| length4 = 3:02\n| title5 = Two Households\n| length5 = 5:00\n| title6 = Incident at a Parade\n| length6 = 2:57\n| title7 = Sabotage\n| length7 = 3:33\n| title8 = Maud\n| length8 = 1:28\n| title9 = Honour Restored\n| length9 = 2:39\n| title10 = Never Seen Anything Like It\n| length10 = 2:27\n| title11 = Not Entirely a Bad Night\n| length11 = 2:59\n| title12 = May I?\n| length12 = 3:08\n| title13 = Taking Leave\n| length13 = 2:26\n| title14 = Resolution\n| length14 = 2:15\n| title15 = You Are the Best of Me\n| length15 = 2:44\n| title16 = Sunset Waltz\n| length16 = 3:51\n| title17 = One Hundred Years of Downton\n| length17 = 5:13\n}}\n\n==Release==\nA companion book and guide to the feature film was available for pre-orders as early as August 2019 to be published on 17 September,<ref name=\"British Period Dramas\">{{cite web|url=http://britishperioddramas.com/news/downton-abbey-the-official-film-companion-book/|title=New book reveals behind the scenes secrets of the 'Downton Abbey' movie \u2013 British Period Dramas|date= 14 August 2019|publisher= British Period Dramas|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref> that is a behind the scenes look at the film production.<ref name=\"Photos Look at Filming\">{{cite web|url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/leisure/arts-and-culture/a28119844/downton-abbey-film-book-julian-fellowes/|title=A Downton Abbey Film Book Will Feature Photos and a Behind-the-Scenes Look at Filming|author= Caroline Hallemann|date= 20 June 2019|publisher= Hearst Magazine Media, Inc.|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"behind-the-scenes Express.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/films/1175769/Downton-Abbey-movie-Lady-Mary-scene-companion-King-George-V-Simon-Jones-Michelle-Dockery|title=Downton Abbey movie behind-the-scenes: King George V and Lady Mary &#124; Films &#124; Entertainment &#124; Express.co.uk|author= George Simpson|date= 9 September 2019|publisher= Express Newspapers|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> The film was released in Australia on 12 September 2019, in the United Kingdom on 13 September 2019, and in the United States on 20 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodhousekeeping.co.uk/news/downton-abbey-movie-release-date-cast-spoilers|title=Everything you need to know about the Downton Abbey movie|date=2 November 2018|publisher=GoodHouseKeeping.co.uk}}</ref> It premiered at [[Leicester Square]] on 9 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www-m.cnn.com/2019/09/09/movies/downton-abbey-movie-premiere-london-intl-scli-gbr/index.html?r=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2F|title=Downton Abbey' stars arrive for world premiere of movie spin-off|date=9 September 2019|website=CNN|accessdate=9 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n{{As of|2019|12|20}}, ''Downton Abbey'' has grossed $96.9 million in the United States and Canada, and $94.9 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $191.8 million.<ref name=\"BOM\" /><ref name=\"NUM\" />\n\nSeveral weeks before its release in the United States, [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] announced ''Downton Abbey''{{'}}s first day advanced ticket sales were pacing ahead of all other adult dramas in 2019, including ''[[Once Upon a Time in Hollywood]]'' ($41.1 million debut that July).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/downton-abbey-fandango-box-office-first-day-sales-1202700908/|title='Downton Abbey' First Day Fandango Presales Bigger Than 'Mamma Mia! Here We Go Again'|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|date=21 August 2019|accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Julian Fellowes Big Screen - WSJ\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/writer-julian-fellowes-prepares-downton-abbey-for-the-big-screen-11568552402|title=Writer Julian Fellowes Prepares 'Downton Abbey' for the Big Screen \u2013 WSJ|author= Chris Kornelis|date= 15 September 2019|publisher= Dow Jones & Company, Inc.|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> A week prior to its release the film held advanced screenings, where it made $2.2 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/will-the-downton-abbey-gang-take-out-rambo-at-the-b-o-weekend-preview-1202738117/|title=Will The 'Downton Abbey' Gang Take Out 'Rambo'? \u2013 Weekend Box Office Preview|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=18 September 2019|access-date=18 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Overall, it was originally projected to gross $16\u201325 million from 3,076 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref name=WrapBudget>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/ad-astra-downton-abbey-rambo-box-office/|title='Ad Astra,' 'Downton Abbey' and 'Rambo' to Bring Box Office Back to Full Speed|last=Fuster|first=Jeremy|website=[[TheWrap]]|date=17 September 2019|access-date=17 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> After making $13.8 million on its first day, including $2.1 million from Thursday night previews, estimates were raised to $31 million. It went on to debut to $31 million, topping the box office and marking the largest opening in Focus Features' history.<ref name=opening>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/downton-abbey-rambo-last-blood-ad-astra-hustlers-weekend-box-office-1202739525/|title='Downton Abbey' $31M Opening Reps Record For Focus Features \u2013 Final Update|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=22 September 2019|access-date=22 September 2019}}</ref> The film made $14.5 million in its second weekend, finishing second behind newcomer ''[[Abominable (2019 film)|Abominable]]'', then $7.9 million in its third, finishing third.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2019/09/abominable-downton-abbey-hustlers-weekend-box-office-1202746278/|title=Dreamworks Animation-Pearl Studios' 'Abominable' Bigfoots B.O. With Near $21M Opening Weekend|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=29 September 2019|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2019/10/joker-box-office-opening-weekend-1202752002//|title= Warner Bros. Laughing All The Way to the Bank With 'Joker': $94M Debut Reps Records For October, Todd Phillips, Joaquin Phoenix & Robert De Niro|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=6 October 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\nAt the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 84% based on 240 reviews, with an average rating of 6.94/10. The website's critics consensus reads, \"''Downton Abbey'' distills many of the ingredients that made the show an enduring favorite, welcoming fans back for a fittingly resplendent homecoming\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Downton Abbey (2019)|url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/downton_abbey/|website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher= [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate= 20 February 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] the film has a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 64 out of 100, based on reviews from 42 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/downton-abbey|title=Downton Abbey reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an average 4.5 out of 5 stars and a 72% \"definite recommend\".<ref name=\"opening\" />\n\nJune Thomas writing for ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' praised the film, writing: \"The plot of the ''Downton Abbey'' movie is brilliant, not so much because it is surprising, but because it allows every member of the cast to do what we expect of them\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2019/09/downton-abbey-movie-review.html|title=In the Downton Abbey Movie, the Servants Finally Revolt!|first=June|last=Thomas|date=9 September 2019|website=Slate Magazine}}</ref> In a more lukewarm reaction, [[Peter Bradshaw]], writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'', said: \"The ''Downton Abbey'' movie is not as spectacularly star-studded as ''[[Gosford Park]]'', but it's got its share of A-list talent, however: Maggie Smith, of course, as the dowager Countess of Grantham, Hugh Bonneville as Lord Grantham (absent-mindedly fondling his retriever at breakfast) \u2013 there's also Imelda Staunton in a new role and Jim Carter as the beetle-browed former butler Mr Carson. All are very underused\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Peter|last=Bradshaw|title=Downton Abbey review \u2013 ridiculous, vanilla-flavoured fun|work=The Guardian|date=9 September 2019|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/sep/10/downton-abbey-review-imelda-staunton-maggie-smith}}</ref>\n\nWriting in the British publication ''[[Radio Times]]'', Eleanor Bley Griffiths writes that Downton the film is \"frankly disappointing\". She explains that \"What the film lacks is any sense of real jeopardy. As we found out from the trailer, the big plot-line is this: the King and Queen are coming to dinner and Downton must be made perfect! But that simple story is stretched out to a full two hours of incredibly low-stakes, predictable drama with an overabundance of sub-plots\". Griffiths goes on to unfavourably compare the new film with the TV series: \"On TV, there was time to explore different threads and highlight specific characters as the series went on; but the movie gives us a whole series-worth of storylines draped over one lacklustre main plot\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Eleanor Bley Griffiths|title= Downton Abbey movie is a disappointing nostalgia trip \u2013 spoiler-free review|url= https://www.radiotimes.com/news/film/2019-09-10/downton-abbey-movie-review/|work=Radio Times|date= 10 September 2019|accessdate= 23 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Popular culture===\nThe cast and crew were featured in a short interview segment on [[PBS]] public television on 20 September 2019, as recognition of the influence which the film and related series have had on American popular culture.<ref>PBS News Hour. ''Downton Abbey Film Interviews''. 20 September 2019. Interviews with Judy Woodruff.</ref>\n\n===Awards, accolades and nominations===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | List of awards, accolades and nominations\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee\n! Result\n|-\n| 2020 || [[AARP|Movies for Grownups Award]] || Best Supporting Actress || [[Maggie Smith]] || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[AARP|Movies for Grownups Award]] || Best Ensemble || ''Downton Abbey'' || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[AARP|Movies for Grownups Award]] || Readers' Choice || ''Downton Abbey'' || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[Alliance of Women Film Journalists|EDA Special Mention Award]] || Actress Defying Age and Ageism || [[Maggie Smith]] || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || Awards Circuit Community Award || Best Costume Design || Anna Robbins || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[Critics Choice Award]] || Best Production Design || Donal Woods<br>Gina Cromwell || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[Critics Choice Award]] || Best Costume Design || Anna Robbins || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || CinEuphoria Award || Best Supporting Actress - International Competition || [[Maggie Smith]] || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || CinEuphoria Award || Best Ensemble - International Competition || [[Hugh Bonneville]]<br>[[Laura Carmichael]]<br>[[Jim Carter (actor)|Jim Carter]]<br>[[Michelle Dockery]]<br>[[Joanne Froggatt]]<br>[[Robert James-Collier]]<br>[[Allen Leech]]<br>[[Elizabeth McGovern]]<br>[[Maggie Smith]]<br>[[Imelda Staunton]] || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[Costume Designers Guild|CDG Award]] || Excellence in Period Film || Anna Robbins || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[GLAAD Media Award]] || Outstanding Film - Wide Release || ''Downton Abbey'' || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[Make-Up Artists and Hair Stylists Guild|Hollywood Makeup Artist and Hair Stylist Guild Award]] || Best Period and/or Character Hair Styling - Feature-Length Motion Picture || Anne Oldham<br>Elaine Browne<br>Marc Pilcher || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[Make-Up Artists and Hair Stylists Guild|Hollywood Makeup Artist and Hair Stylist Guild Award]] || Best Period and/or Character Makeup - Feature-Length Motion Picture || Anne Oldham<br>Elaine Browne<br>Sam Smart || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2019 || [[Hollywood Film Awards|Hollywood Film Award]] || Costume Designer of the Year || Anna Robbins || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2019 || [[San Diego Film Critics Society|SDFCS Award]] || Best Costume Design || Anna Robbins || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2019 || [[San Diego Film Critics Society|SDFCS Award]] || Best Production Design || Donal Woods || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2019 || [[San Diego Film Critics Society|SDFCS Award]] || Best Ensemble || ''Downton Abbey'' || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2019 || [[Satellite Awards|Satellite Award]] || Best Costume Design || Anna Robbins || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2019 || [[Seattle Film Critics Society|Seattle Film Critics Award]] || Best Costume Design || Anna Robbins || {{Nominated}}\n|}\n\n==Future==\nAfter the release of the film, the creator [[Julian Fellowes]] and the cast stated that they already have ideas about doing a potential sequel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/09/24/downton-abbey-potential-sequel-ideas/|title= Downton Abbey team says they already have ideas for a potential sequel|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last1=Lee Lenker|first1=Maureen|date=24 September 2019|accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|first=Jessica|last=Fellowes|title=A Year in the Life of Downton Abbey: Seasonal Celebrations, Traditions, and Recipes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=esZzAwAAQBAJ|date=2014|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-1-4668-7221-9|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first=Jessica|last=Fellowes|title=Downton Abbey - A Celebration: The Official Companion to All Six Seasons|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AJUzCgAAQBAJ|date=2015|publisher=St. Martin's Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-250-09156-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first1=Jessica|last=Fellowes|first2=Matthew|last2=Sturgis|title=The Chronicles of Downton Abbey: A New Era|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TJyg0RN-ue8C&pg=PA99|date=13 November 2012|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-1-250-02762-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first=Jessica|last=Fellowes|title=The World of Downton Abbey|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NHbTXPpgRyAC&pg=PT13|date=2011|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-1-250-01620-1|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.focusfeatures.com/downton-abbey}}\n*{{IMDb title|tt6398184}}\n{{Downton Abbey}}\n{{Julian Fellowes}}{{Michael Engler}}\n{{George V}}\n[[Category:Downton Abbey]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British drama films]]\n[[Category:British historical films]]\n[[Category:Films based on television series]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Focus Features films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1927]]\n[[Category:Films set in England]]\n[[Category:Films set in country houses]]\n[[Category:Films about social class]]\n[[Category:Domestic workers in films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of George V]]\n[[Category:British LGBT-related films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Historical drama film directed by Michael Engler}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Downton Abbey\n| image = DowntonAbbey2019Poster.jpg\n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Michael Engler]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Julian Fellowes]]\n* [[Gareth Neame]]\n* Liz Trubridge\n}}\n| screenplay = Julian Fellowes\n| based on = {{Based on|''[[Downton Abbey]]''|Julian Fellowes}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Hugh Bonneville]]\n* [[Jim Carter (actor)|Jim Carter]]\n* [[Michelle Dockery]]\n* [[Elizabeth McGovern]]\n* [[Maggie Smith]]\n* [[Imelda Staunton]]\n* [[Penelope Wilton]]\n}}\n| music = [[John Lunn]]\n| cinematography = Ben Smithard\n| editing = [[Mark Day (editor)|Mark Day]]\n| studio = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Perfect World Pictures]]\n* [[Focus Features]]\n* [[Carnival Films]]<ref name=\"Distributor\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/downton-abbey-movie-gets-go-ahead-with-series-cast-returning-1202872674/|title='Downton Abbey' Movie Officially a Go With Series Cast Returning|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=13 July 2018|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| distributor = {{unbulleted list|[[Universal Pictures UK]] (United Kingdom)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/downton-abbey-film|title=DOWNTON ABBEY &#124; British Board of Film Classification|website=bbfc.co.uk}}</ref>|Focus Features (United States)}}\n| released = {{Film date|df=yes|2019|9|9|[[Leicester Square]]|2019|9|13|United Kingdom|2019|9|20|United States}}\n| runtime = 122 minutes\n| country =  {{unbulleted list|United Kingdom|United States}}\n| language = English\n| budget = $13\u201320 million<ref name=\"WrapBudget\" /><ref name=\"opening\" />\n| gross = $194 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|title= Downton Abbey (2019)|url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=downtonabbey.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NUM\">{{cite web|title=Downton Abbey (2019)|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Downton-Abbey-(UK)-(2019)#tab=summary|website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Downton Abbey''''' is a 2019 [[historical drama film]] written by [[Julian Fellowes]], creator and writer of the [[Downton Abbey|television series of the same name]],<ref name=\"urlJulian Fellowes List of Movies and TV Shows|TV Guide\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/julian-fellowes/credits/159291/#33e34403ada425d45e7ed27b1f23849f|title=Julian Fellowes List of Movies and TV Shows &#124; TV Guide|publisher= CBS Interactive Inc.|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref> produced by [[Gareth Neame]], Liz Trubridge and Fellowes, and directed by [[Michael Engler]]. The film is a [[Carnival Films]] production, with [[Focus Features]] and Universal Pictures International distributing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.focusfeatures.com/article/production-announcement_downton-abbey-movie|title=Focus Features Announces Production on the Downton Abbey Movie|website=Focus Features|language=en|access-date=22 September 2019}}</ref> and continues the storyline from the series, with much of the original cast returning.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/film/2018-12-23/downton-abbey-bosses-reveal-why-they-didnt-bring-back-lily-james-for-the-movie/|title=Downton Abbey bosses reveal why they didn't bring back Lily James for the movie|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=23 December 2018|accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref> The film, set in 1927, depicts a visit by the King and Queen to the Crawley family's [[English country house]] in the Yorkshire countryside. As the Royal staff descend on Downton, an assassin has also arrived and attempts to kill the monarch. The family and servants are pitted against the royal entourage, including the Queen's [[lady-in-waiting]], who has fallen out with the Crawleys, especially the Dowager Countess, over an inheritance issue.\n\n[[Gareth Neame]] and Fellowes started planning a feature adaptation in 2016, shortly after the series ended. It was officially confirmed in July 2018 and filming began later that month, lasting through November. The film was released in the United Kingdom on 13 September 2019, and in the United States on 20 September 2019. It received generally positive reviews from critics and grossed $192 million worldwide.\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1927, about a year and a half after the TV series ended. [[Buckingham Palace]] informs Robert and Cora Crawley, the Earl and Countess of Grantham, that [[George V|King George V]] and [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]] will visit Downton Abbey during a royal tour through [[Yorkshire]]. Violet Crawley, Dowager Countess of Grantham, is perturbed that Maud, Lady Bagshaw, Queen Mary's lady-in-waiting, is included in the tour. Robert is Maud's cousin and closest relative, and the two families have long disputed who should inherit Maud's estate.\n\nThe [[Royal Households of the United Kingdom|royal household staff]] arrive, including Mr Wilson, the Royal [[Page of the Backstairs]]; Mrs Webb, the Royal Housekeeper; Miss Lawton, the Queen's Royal Dresser; Monsieur Courbet, the Royal Chef; and Richard Ellis, the King's Royal Dresser. All but Ellis are dismissive and arrogant to the Downton servants. Upstairs, eldest Crawley daughter Lady Mary Talbot, the estate manager, constantly worries about keeping Downton afloat in a fast-changing world. Believing Mr Barrow cannot manage a royal visit, Mary asks Mr Carson, Downton's retired butler, to temporarily resume his duties. Barrow, strongly protesting, steps aside.\n\nMajor Chetwode arrives in Downton Village seeking out the Granthams' Irish son-in-law, Tom Branson. Tom assumes Chetwode is a detective assessing security for the royal visit. Prior to the royal parade starting through Downton Village, Chetwode stations himself near where the King is awaiting the Royal Artillery, unaware that Tom has grown suspicious. As Chetwode aims a pistol at King George, Tom tackles Chetwode, pinning him to the ground. The real royal detectives apprehend Chetwode, an Irish Republican sympathizer who erroneously believed Tom was an ally.\n\nThe royal entourage has completely displaced the Downton household. Meanwhile, Tom and Lucy Smith, Lady Maud's maid, form a mutual attraction. Bertie and Edith Pelham, the Marquess and Marchioness of Hexham, also arrive at Downton. The King asks Bertie to accompany the [[Edward VIII|Prince of Wales]] on a three-month African tour. The news distresses Edith, the younger Crawley daughter, who tells Bertie she is pregnant and is due just as Bertie would depart. In the garden, Tom encounters a sobbing woman, unaware she is [[Mary, Princess Royal and Countess of Harewood|Princess Mary]]. He initiates a conversation which inspires the Princess to remain with her [[Henry Lascelles, 6th Earl of Harewood|husband]]. Meanwhile, Anna discovers Miss Lawton is stealing small objects from Downton Abbey. She demands their return, then blackmails Lawton into [[dress fitting|altering]] an over-sized ballgown to fit Lady Edith after the wrong dress was mistakenly delivered to Downton.\n\nAnna and John Bates unite the staff into retaking control downstairs to defend Downton's honour. Barrow and Mr Ellis trick some royal household staff into returning to London. Anna slips a strong sleeping aid into Courbet's tea, and Mr Wilson is \"accidentally\" locked inside his room, allowing Mrs Patmore and Daisy to cook the dinner, and Mr Carson and the Downton footmen to wait at table. When the King praises the revised menu, Molesley impulsively blurts out that the Downton staff prepared the meal and are serving it. Robert apologises for Molesley's inappropriate outburst, but the Queen says they are accustomed to people behaving strangely around them.\n\nThat same evening, Barrow and Ellis go to [[York]]. While Ellis visits his parents, Barrow waits at a local pub. A man there invites Barrow to a hidden gay nightclub. Shortly after Barrow arrives, police raid the club. Ellis, who is secretly gay, discovers what happened and uses his royal connection to secure Barrow's release. Afterwards, the two men develop a bond, indicating they will meet again.\n\nBack at Downton, as the inheritance conflict escalates, Isobel, Lady Merton, surmises correctly that Lucy is Maud's secret illegitimate daughter, which is the reason she is Maud's heir. She tells Maud she must inform Violet. The next morning, assistant cook Daisy, who doubted if footman Andy was the right man for her, realizes she does love him and begins planning their wedding. Henry Talbot, Mary's husband, returns from abroad in time to accompany the family to [[Harewood House]] with the royal party.\n\nDuring the ball at Harewood, Princess Mary informs her parents that Tom inspired her to save her marriage, prompting the King to personally thank him. Also, the Queen has persuaded the King to release Bertie from the imminent tour. Maud tells Violet about Lucy. Violet does not approve but understands, and immediately schemes to unite the two households through Lucy and Tom when told they plan to write to one another. Mary privately queries her grandmother regarding her recent trip to [[London]]. Violet confides that medical tests reveal she may die soon, but she assures a distraught Mary that Downton's legacy is safe in her hands. Tom later seeks out Lucy on the terrace and dances with her.\n\nMr Carson and Mrs Hughes ponder Downton's future in the modern era. Carson asserts it will stand for another hundred years with the Crawley family still in residence.\n\n==Cast==\n{{see also|List of Downton Abbey characters}}\n{{cast list|\n* [[Hugh Bonneville]] as Robert Crawley, 7th Earl of Grantham\n* [[Laura Carmichael]] as Edith Pelham (n\u00e9e Crawley), Marchioness of Hexham\n* [[Jim Carter (actor)|Jim Carter]] as Charles Carson\n* [[Raquel Cassidy]] as Phyllis Baxter\n* [[Brendan Coyle]] as John Bates\n* [[Michelle Dockery]] as Lady Mary Talbot (n\u00e9e Crawley)\n* [[Kevin Doyle (actor)|Kevin Doyle]] as Joseph Molesley\n* [[Michael C. Fox]] as Andy Parker\n* [[Joanne Froggatt]] as Anna Bates\n* [[Matthew Goode]] as Henry Talbot\n* [[Harry Hadden-Paton]] as Bertie Pelham, 7th Marquess of Hexham\n* [[Robert James-Collier]] as Thomas Barrow\n* [[Allen Leech]] as Tom Branson\n* [[Phyllis Logan]] as Elsie Hughes\n* [[Elizabeth McGovern]] as Cora Crawley, Countess of Grantham\n* [[Sophie McShera]] as Daisy Mason\n* [[Lesley Nicol (actress)|Lesley Nicol]] as Beryl Patmore\n* [[Maggie Smith]] as Violet Crawley, Dowager Countess of Grantham\n* [[Imelda Staunton]] as Maud, Lady Bagshaw\n* [[Penelope Wilton]] as Isobel, Lady Merton\n* [[Mark Addy]] as Mr Bakewell\n* [[Max Brown (actor)|Max Brown]] as Richard Ellis\n* [[Stephen Campbell Moore]] as Major Chetwode\n* [[Richenda Carey]] as Mrs Webb\n* [[David Haig]] as Mr Wilson\n* [[Andrew Havill]] as [[Henry Lascelles, 6th Earl of Harewood|Henry, Viscount Lascelles]]\n* [[Geraldine James]] as [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]]\n* [[Simon Jones (actor)|Simon Jones]] as [[George V|King George V]]\n* [[Susan Lynch]] as Miss Lawton\n* [[Tuppence Middleton]] as Lucy Smith\n* [[Kate Phillips (British actress)|Kate Phillips]] as [[Mary, Princess Royal and Countess of Harewood|The Princess Mary, Viscountess Lascelles]]\n* James Cartwright as Tony Sellick\n* Douglas Reith as Richard, Lord Merton\n* Philippe Spall as Monsieur Courbet\n* Oliver and Zac Barker as Master George\n* Fifi Hart as Miss Sybbie\n* Eva and Karina Samms as Miss Marigold\n}}\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Highclere Castle (April 2011).jpg|thumb|right|[[Highclere Castle]], the site used as the fictional Downton Abbey estate.]]\n===Development===\nThe original television series, ''Downton Abbey'', ended in 2015, after 52 episodes<ref name=\"HowardBianculli2018\">{{cite book|author1=Douglas L. Howard|author2=David Bianculli|title=Television Finales: From Howdy Doody to Girls|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5nN0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA105|date=13 November 2018|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=978-0-8156-5447-6|page=105}}</ref><ref name=\"url'Downton Abbey' Series Finale Recap: The End of An Era \u2013 Variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/downton-abbey-series-finale-recap-1201706224/|title='Downton Abbey' Series Finale Recap: The End of An Era \u2013 Variety|author= Debra Birnbaum|date= 6 March 2016|publisher= Variety Media, LLC, a subsidiary of Penske Business Media, LLC.|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ceciliarodriguez/2018/07/15/downton-abbey-is-returning-with-the-original-cast-to-the-movies/#3289ab44863c|title=Downton Abbey Is Returning, With The Original Cast, To The Movies|publisher=[[Forbes]]|work=forbes.com|date=15 July 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref> with its final episode set at New Year's Eve, 1925.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Picturehouse Cinemas Ltd.|date=2019|title=Coming Soon: Downton Abbey|journal=Picturehouse Recommends|volume=May/June/July|pages=6}}</ref> In April 2016, it was revealed that a [[film adaptation]] was being considered,<ref>{{cite news|work=The Telegraph|date= 10 April 2016|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2016/04/10/downton-creator-julian-fellowes-why-the-personal-attacks-hurt-so/|title=Downton creator Julian Fellowes: 'Why the personal attacks hurt so much'|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref> with [[Julian Fellowes]] working on an outline plot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/entertainment-arts-36049641/julian-fellowes-i-m-plotting-downton-abbey-film|title=Julian Fellowes: I'm plotting Downton Abbey film|publisher=[[BBC News]]|work=bbc.co.uk/news|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref> A script was distributed to original cast members early in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-39326666|title=Downton Abbey movie 'could be filmed this year'|publisher=[[BBC News]]|work=bbc.co.uk/news|date=20 March 2017|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2018-08-12/downton-abbeys-phyllis-logan-reveals-production-on-the-movie-begins-any-minute-now/|title=Downton Abbey's Phyllis Logan reveals production on the movie begins 'any minute now'|publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]]|work=[[Radio times]]|date=12 August 2018|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 July 2018, the producers confirmed that a feature-length film would be made,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-44822420|title=Downton Abbey film (finally) confirmed|publisher=[[BBC News]]|work=bbc.co.uk/news|date=13 July 2018|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref> with production commencing mid-2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jul/13/downton-abbey-film-confirmed-to-shoot-this-summer-with-series-cast-returning|title=Downton Abbey film confirmed to shoot this summer with series cast returning|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=13 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"forbes\"/> The script was written by Fellowes. The producers are [[Gareth Neame]], Liz Trubridge and Fellowes.<ref name=\"vanityfair.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/07/downton-abbey-movie-cast-summer/|title=It's Happening: Downton Abbey's Original Cast Is Reuniting for a Movie|first=Yohana|last=Desta|publisher=Vanity Fair}}</ref> The film is distributed by [[Focus Features]] and [[Universal Pictures International]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/13/movies/downton-abbey-movie.html|title='Downton Abbey' Movie Is on the Way|work=The New York Times|date=13 July 2018|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref> In late August 2018, it was reported that [[Brian Percival]] had stepped down as director and [[Michael Engler]] took on this job. Percival, in addition to Nigel Marchant, would be an executive producer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/downton-abbey-movie-filming/|title='Downton Abbey' Movie Due to Begin Filming as Cast Grows, Director Replaced|date=31 August 2018|publisher=Collider}}</ref><ref name=\"variety.com\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/imelda-staunton-geraldine-james-downton-abbey-movie-1202922680/|title=Imelda Staunton, Geraldine James Join 'Downton Abbey' Movie|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=30 August 2018|publisher=Variety}}</ref>\n\nThe plot of the film is based on an actual trip by the British royals to [[Wentworth Woodhouse]] in 1912 in order to demonstrate the importance of the monarchy. The estate itself was used as part of the shooting locations because of the story's link to that history.<ref name=\"New Era for the Household\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/when-does-the-downton-abbey-movie-take-place-its-a-new-era-for-the-household-18724874|title=When Does The 'Downton Abbey' Movie Take Place? It's A New Era for the Household|author= Jasmine Ting|date= 16 September 2019|publisher= BUSTLE|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nOriginal cast members including Hugh Bonneville, Elizabeth McGovern, Michelle Dockery, Laura Carmichael and Maggie Smith, were confirmed to return as their characters from the series,<ref name=\"vanityfair.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/maggie-smith-83-to-be-in-downton-abbey-movie/|title=Maggie Smith, 83, to Return for&nbsp;Downton Abbey Big Screen Movie Alongside TV Show's Main Cast|publisher=People.com}}</ref> with Joanne Froggatt confirming her involvement in a separate announcement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.accessonline.com/articles/downton-abbey-movie-coming-and-joanne-froggatt-and-michelle-dockery-are-beyond-excited-about-it/|title=A 'Downton Abbey' Movie Is Coming and Joanne Froggatt and Michelle Dockery Are Beyond Excited About It|publisher=[[KNBC]]|work=[[Access (American TV program)|Access]]|date=13 July 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref> [[Lily James]], who played Lady Rose MacClare, stated she would not be reprising her role for the film,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/lily-james-not-returning-downton-abbey-movie/|title=Lily James Reveals Why There's 'No Space' for Her in Downton Abbey Movie|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=15 July 2018|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2018/07/16/lily-james-will-not-returning-downton-abbey-movie/|title=Lily James will not be returning for the Downton Abbey movie|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=16 July 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018|last1=Corrodus|first1=Corrine}}</ref> as did [[Ed Speleers]] who played footman Jimmy Kent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/downton-abbey/news/a870372/downton-abbey-ed-speleers-not-returning-movie/|title=Downton Abbey star Ed Speleers won't be returning for the film|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=11 November 2018|accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn August 2018 announcement indicated that newcomers Imelda Staunton, Geraldine James, Tuppence Middleton, Simon Jones, David Haig, Kate Phillips, and Stephen Campbell Moore would be among the cast of the film.<ref name=\"variety.com\"/> The producers told the news media that Simon Jones and Geraldine James play the King and Queen, respectively (although not shown in the trailer), while David Haig appears as the King's butler.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.journalpost.com/entertainment/celeb/downton-abbey-is-back-with-an-all-new-movie-trailer/|title='Downton Abbey' is back with an all-new movie trailer|newspaper=Journal Post|date=24 May 2019|access-date=26 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, it was confirmed that Matthew Goode, who played Lady Mary's husband Henry Talbot in the final series, appears only briefly due to other commitments,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-09-03/downton-abbey-movie-matthew-goode-cast-confirmed/|title=Matthew Goode confirmed for Downton Abbey movie&nbsp;\u2013 but he says he will only be \"popping in at the end\"|work=[[Radio Times]]}}</ref> while Jim Carter, Brendan Coyle, Kevin Doyle, Harry Hadden-Paton, Rob James-Collier, Allen Leech, Phyllis Logan, Sophie McShera, Lesley Nicol and Penelope Wilton were confirmed to be reprising their respective roles, with Max Brown joining in a new, undisclosed role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/downton-abbey-movie-sets-fall-2019-opening-1202467698/|title='Downton Abbey' Movie Sets Fall 2019 Opening|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=19 September 2018|publisher=Deadline Hollywood}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/downton-abbey-movie-cast-max-brown-the-royals-1202472427/|title='Downton Abbey' Movie Adds 'The Royals' Max Brown|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=27 September 2018|publisher=Deadline Hollywood}}</ref>\n\n===Costumes===\nCostumes were designed by Anna Mary Scott Robbins working with John Bright of the costume company COSPROP in London, which specializes in historic, period costumes.<ref name=\"Scott Robbins COSPROP\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/09/13/downton-abbey-movie-costumes/|title=Diamonds! Vintage gowns! Inside the Downton Abbey movie costumes fit for a queen|author= Rosy Cordero|date= 13 September 2019|publisher= Meredith Corporation|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref> The company has some of Queen Mary's real wardrobe, studied for details of construction.<ref name=\"Scott Robbins COSPROP\" /> Geraldine James' Queen Mary costume was constructed using material from one of the Queen's actual dresses.<ref name=\"Scott Robbins COSPROP\" /> During the Ball scene, both Michelle Dockery and Elizabeth McGovern wore vintage dresses that were embellished with additional work. Dockery's beaded French gown had beads lengthened to the floor by hand. While Michelle Dockery wears [[Swarovski crystals]] in her tiara, Maggie Smith's is a 19th-century platinum piece<ref name=\"Scott Robbins COSPROP\" /> from Bentley & Skinner of Piccadilly jewellers by Royal appointment<ref name=\"Bentley & Skinner\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bentley-skinner.co.uk/|title=Welcome to Bentley & Skinner \u2013 Bentley & Skinner, the Mayfair antique and bespoke jewellery shop in the heart of London|publisher= Bentley & Skinner (Bond Street Jewellers) Ltd|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref> with 16.5 carats of diamonds. Smith's ball gown was found in a vintage shop in Paris and dye was used to alter the turquoise color to lilac.<ref name=\"Scott Robbins COSPROP\" />\n\n===Filming===\nPrincipal photography started in London in late August 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2456786/the-downton-abbey-movie-has-officially-started-filming|title=The Downton Abbey Movie Has Officially Started Filming|publisher=Gateway Blend|work=Cinemablend|date=1 September 2018|accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"variety.com\"/> By 20 September, some filming was under way at [[Highclere Castle]], Hampshire, which had been the main location for the television series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/movies/downton-abbey-movie-first-images-of-the-lavish-country-set-are-unveiled-as-filming-on-the-eagerly-anticipated-film-gets-underway-at-highclere-castle/ar-BBNALEo|title=Downton Abbey movie: FIRST images of the lavish country set are unveiled as filming on the eagerly anticipated film gets underway at Highclere Castle|publisher=[[MSN]]|work=MSN Entertainment|date=20 September 2018|accessdate=25 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highclerecastle.co.uk/downton-abbey-movie-confirmed|title=DOWNTON ABBEY MOVIE CONFIRMED|publisher=[[Highclere Castle]]|work=express.co.uk|date=5 August 2018|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref> Also in September, filming was under way in [[Lacock]], [[Wiltshire]], with Dame Maggie Smith, Hugh Bonneville, Elizabeth McGovern and Michelle Dockery as well as two new cast members, Imelda Staunton (wife of Jim Carter) and Geraldine James; scenes shot in Lacock included a celebration with horses from the [[Royal Artillery]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gazetteandherald.co.uk/news/16952909.lacock-transformed-for-downton-movie-filming/|title=Downton stars return to Lacock for movie filming|last=Moore|first=Joanne|date=1 October 2018|website=The Wiltshire Gazette and Herald|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=15 December 2018}}</ref> Exterior scenes set in York were filmed on location at [[Beamish Museum]], complete with operational [[tram]]s.<ref name=\"beamish\">{{cite web|title=New Downton Abbey Film at Beamish Museum|url=http://www.beamish.org.uk/news/new-downton-abbey-film-at-beamish-museum/|website=Beamish|accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref> The Heritage Railways scenes were filmed on the North Yorkshire Moors Railway with Pickering terminus representing Kings Cross. The Royal Mail Sorting Office Coach was borrowed from the Great Central Railway at Loughborough. Filming concluded in November 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/allen-leech-interview-bohemian-rhapsody-downton-abbey-movie/|title=Allen Leech on Making 'Bohemian Rhapsody' and the 'Downton Abbey' Movie|work=Collider|publisher=Collider|date=8 November 2018|accessdate=9 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name = Downton Abbey\n| type = soundtrack\n| artist = [[John Lunn]]\n| released = September 13, 2019\n| recorded = 2019\n| genre = [[Soundtrack album]]<br>[[Film score]]\n| length = 53:07\n| label = [[Decca Gold]]<br>[[Decca Records]]<br> [[Universal Music Group#Toronto|Universal Music Canada]]\n| producer = [[John Lunn]]\n}}\n'''''Downton Abbey''''' is the film\u2019s soundtrack album and musical score album of the same name, composed by [[John Lunn]], conducted and orchestrated by Alastair King, edited by Mark Willsher and performed by [[London Chamber Orchestra|The Chamber Orchestra of London]] with additional music composed by [[Chris Egan (musician)|Chris Egan]] and prepared by Tristan Noon, while the music for the film\u2019s trailer was composed by David James Rosen. It was released on September 13, 2019 on CD, digital download and vinyl by [[Decca Gold]], [[Decca Records]] and [[Universal Music Group#Toronto|Universal Music Canada]].\n\n===Track listing===\n{{Track listing\n| all_music = [[John Lunn]]\n| total_length = 53:07\n| title1 = A Royal Command\n| length1 = 4:49\n| title2 = Pillar of the Establishment\n| length2 = 1:48\n| title3 = Gleam and Sparkle\n| length3 = 2:48\n| title4 = God Is a Monarchist\n| length4 = 3:02\n| title5 = Two Households\n| length5 = 5:00\n| title6 = Incident at a Parade\n| length6 = 2:57\n| title7 = Sabotage\n| length7 = 3:33\n| title8 = Maud\n| length8 = 1:28\n| title9 = Honour Restored\n| length9 = 2:39\n| title10 = Never Seen Anything Like It\n| length10 = 2:27\n| title11 = Not Entirely a Bad Night\n| length11 = 2:59\n| title12 = May I?\n| length12 = 3:08\n| title13 = Taking Leave\n| length13 = 2:26\n| title14 = Resolution\n| length14 = 2:15\n| title15 = You Are the Best of Me\n| length15 = 2:44\n| title16 = Sunset Waltz\n| length16 = 3:51\n| title17 = One Hundred Years of Downton\n| length17 = 5:13\n}}\n\n==Release==\nA companion book and guide to the feature film was available for pre-orders as early as August 2019 to be published on 17 September,<ref name=\"British Period Dramas\">{{cite web|url=http://britishperioddramas.com/news/downton-abbey-the-official-film-companion-book/|title=New book reveals behind the scenes secrets of the 'Downton Abbey' movie \u2013 British Period Dramas|date= 14 August 2019|publisher= British Period Dramas|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref> that is a behind the scenes look at the film production.<ref name=\"Photos Look at Filming\">{{cite web|url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/leisure/arts-and-culture/a28119844/downton-abbey-film-book-julian-fellowes/|title=A Downton Abbey Film Book Will Feature Photos and a Behind-the-Scenes Look at Filming|author= Caroline Hallemann|date= 20 June 2019|publisher= Hearst Magazine Media, Inc.|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"behind-the-scenes Express.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/films/1175769/Downton-Abbey-movie-Lady-Mary-scene-companion-King-George-V-Simon-Jones-Michelle-Dockery|title=Downton Abbey movie behind-the-scenes: King George V and Lady Mary &#124; Films &#124; Entertainment &#124; Express.co.uk|author= George Simpson|date= 9 September 2019|publisher= Express Newspapers|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> The film was released in Australia on 12 September 2019, in the United Kingdom on 13 September 2019, and in the United States on 20 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodhousekeeping.co.uk/news/downton-abbey-movie-release-date-cast-spoilers|title=Everything you need to know about the Downton Abbey movie|date=2 November 2018|publisher=GoodHouseKeeping.co.uk}}</ref> It premiered at [[Leicester Square]] on 9 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www-m.cnn.com/2019/09/09/movies/downton-abbey-movie-premiere-london-intl-scli-gbr/index.html?r=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2F|title=Downton Abbey' stars arrive for world premiere of movie spin-off|date=9 September 2019|website=CNN|accessdate=9 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n{{As of|2019|12|20}}, ''Downton Abbey'' has grossed $96.9 million in the United States and Canada, and $94.9 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $191.8 million.<ref name=\"BOM\" /><ref name=\"NUM\" />\n\nSeveral weeks before its release in the United States, [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] announced ''Downton Abbey''{{'}}s first day advanced ticket sales were pacing ahead of all other adult dramas in 2019, including ''[[Once Upon a Time in Hollywood]]'' ($41.1 million debut that July).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/downton-abbey-fandango-box-office-first-day-sales-1202700908/|title='Downton Abbey' First Day Fandango Presales Bigger Than 'Mamma Mia! Here We Go Again'|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|date=21 August 2019|accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Julian Fellowes Big Screen - WSJ\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/writer-julian-fellowes-prepares-downton-abbey-for-the-big-screen-11568552402|title=Writer Julian Fellowes Prepares 'Downton Abbey' for the Big Screen \u2013 WSJ|author= Chris Kornelis|date= 15 September 2019|publisher= Dow Jones & Company, Inc.|accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> A week prior to its release the film held advanced screenings, where it made $2.2 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/will-the-downton-abbey-gang-take-out-rambo-at-the-b-o-weekend-preview-1202738117/|title=Will The 'Downton Abbey' Gang Take Out 'Rambo'? \u2013 Weekend Box Office Preview|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=18 September 2019|access-date=18 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Overall, it was originally projected to gross $16\u201325 million from 3,076 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref name=WrapBudget>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/ad-astra-downton-abbey-rambo-box-office/|title='Ad Astra,' 'Downton Abbey' and 'Rambo' to Bring Box Office Back to Full Speed|last=Fuster|first=Jeremy|website=[[TheWrap]]|date=17 September 2019|access-date=17 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> After making $13.8 million on its first day, including $2.1 million from Thursday night previews, estimates were raised to $31 million. It went on to debut to $31 million, topping the box office and marking the largest opening in Focus Features' history.<ref name=opening>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/downton-abbey-rambo-last-blood-ad-astra-hustlers-weekend-box-office-1202739525/|title='Downton Abbey' $31M Opening Reps Record For Focus Features \u2013 Final Update|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=22 September 2019|access-date=22 September 2019}}</ref> The film made $14.5 million in its second weekend, finishing second behind newcomer ''[[Abominable (2019 film)|Abominable]]'', then $7.9 million in its third, finishing third.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2019/09/abominable-downton-abbey-hustlers-weekend-box-office-1202746278/|title=Dreamworks Animation-Pearl Studios' 'Abominable' Bigfoots B.O. With Near $21M Opening Weekend|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=29 September 2019|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2019/10/joker-box-office-opening-weekend-1202752002//|title= Warner Bros. Laughing All The Way to the Bank With 'Joker': $94M Debut Reps Records For October, Todd Phillips, Joaquin Phoenix & Robert De Niro|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=6 October 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\nAt the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 84% based on 240 reviews, with an average rating of 6.94/10. The website's critics consensus reads, \"''Downton Abbey'' distills many of the ingredients that made the show an enduring favorite, welcoming fans back for a fittingly resplendent homecoming\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Downton Abbey (2019)|url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/downton_abbey/|website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher= [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate= 20 February 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] the film has a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 64 out of 100, based on reviews from 42 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/downton-abbey|title=Downton Abbey reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an average 4.5 out of 5 stars and a 72% \"definite recommend\".<ref name=\"opening\" />\n\nJune Thomas writing for ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' praised the film, writing: \"The plot of the ''Downton Abbey'' movie is brilliant, not so much because it is surprising, but because it allows every member of the cast to do what we expect of them\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2019/09/downton-abbey-movie-review.html|title=In the Downton Abbey Movie, the Servants Finally Revolt!|first=June|last=Thomas|date=9 September 2019|website=Slate Magazine}}</ref> In a more lukewarm reaction, [[Peter Bradshaw]], writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'', said: \"The ''Downton Abbey'' movie is not as spectacularly star-studded as ''[[Gosford Park]]'', but it's got its share of A-list talent, however: Maggie Smith, of course, as the dowager Countess of Grantham, Hugh Bonneville as Lord Grantham (absent-mindedly fondling his retriever at breakfast) \u2013 there's also Imelda Staunton in a new role and Jim Carter as the beetle-browed former butler Mr Carson. All are very underused\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Peter|last=Bradshaw|title=Downton Abbey review \u2013 ridiculous, vanilla-flavoured fun|work=The Guardian|date=9 September 2019|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/sep/10/downton-abbey-review-imelda-staunton-maggie-smith}}</ref>\n\nWriting in the British publication ''[[Radio Times]]'', Eleanor Bley Griffiths writes that Downton the film is \"frankly disappointing\". She explains that \"What the film lacks is any sense of real jeopardy. As we found out from the trailer, the big plot-line is this: the King and Queen are coming to dinner and Downton must be made perfect! But that simple story is stretched out to a full two hours of incredibly low-stakes, predictable drama with an overabundance of sub-plots\". Griffiths goes on to unfavourably compare the new film with the TV series: \"On TV, there was time to explore different threads and highlight specific characters as the series went on; but the movie gives us a whole series-worth of storylines draped over one lacklustre main plot\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Eleanor Bley Griffiths|title= Downton Abbey movie is a disappointing nostalgia trip \u2013 spoiler-free review|url= https://www.radiotimes.com/news/film/2019-09-10/downton-abbey-movie-review/|work=Radio Times|date= 10 September 2019|accessdate= 23 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Popular culture===\nThe cast and crew were featured in a short interview segment on [[PBS]] public television on 20 September 2019, as recognition of the influence which the film and related series have had on American popular culture.<ref>PBS News Hour. ''Downton Abbey Film Interviews''. 20 September 2019. Interviews with Judy Woodruff.</ref>\n\n===Awards, accolades and nominations===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | List of awards, accolades and nominations\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee\n! Result\n|-\n| 2020 || [[AARP|Movies for Grownups Award]] || Best Supporting Actress || [[Maggie Smith]] || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[AARP|Movies for Grownups Award]] || Best Ensemble || ''Downton Abbey'' || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[AARP|Movies for Grownups Award]] || Readers' Choice || ''Downton Abbey'' || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[Alliance of Women Film Journalists|EDA Special Mention Award]] || Actress Defying Age and Ageism || [[Maggie Smith]] || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || Awards Circuit Community Award || Best Costume Design || Anna Robbins || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[Critics Choice Award]] || Best Production Design || Donal Woods<br>Gina Cromwell || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[Critics Choice Award]] || Best Costume Design || Anna Robbins || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || CinEuphoria Award || Best Supporting Actress - International Competition || [[Maggie Smith]] || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || CinEuphoria Award || Best Ensemble - International Competition || [[Hugh Bonneville]]<br>[[Laura Carmichael]]<br>[[Jim Carter (actor)|Jim Carter]]<br>[[Michelle Dockery]]<br>[[Joanne Froggatt]]<br>[[Robert James-Collier]]<br>[[Allen Leech]]<br>[[Elizabeth McGovern]]<br>[[Maggie Smith]]<br>[[Imelda Staunton]] || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[Costume Designers Guild|CDG Award]] || Excellence in Period Film || Anna Robbins || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[GLAAD Media Award]] || Outstanding Film - Wide Release || ''Downton Abbey'' || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[Make-Up Artists and Hair Stylists Guild|Hollywood Makeup Artist and Hair Stylist Guild Award]] || Best Period and/or Character Hair Styling - Feature-Length Motion Picture || Anne Oldham<br>Elaine Browne<br>Marc Pilcher || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2020 || [[Make-Up Artists and Hair Stylists Guild|Hollywood Makeup Artist and Hair Stylist Guild Award]] || Best Period and/or Character Makeup - Feature-Length Motion Picture || Anne Oldham<br>Elaine Browne<br>Sam Smart || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2019 || [[Hollywood Film Awards|Hollywood Film Award]] || Costume Designer of the Year || Anna Robbins || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2019 || [[San Diego Film Critics Society|SDFCS Award]] || Best Costume Design || Anna Robbins || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2019 || [[San Diego Film Critics Society|SDFCS Award]] || Best Production Design || Donal Woods || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2019 || [[San Diego Film Critics Society|SDFCS Award]] || Best Ensemble || ''Downton Abbey'' || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2019 || [[Satellite Awards|Satellite Award]] || Best Costume Design || Anna Robbins || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| 2019 || [[Seattle Film Critics Society|Seattle Film Critics Award]] || Best Costume Design || Anna Robbins || {{Nominated}}\n|}\n\n==Future==\nAfter the release of the film, the creator [[Julian Fellowes]] and the cast stated that they already have ideas about doing a potential sequel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/09/24/downton-abbey-potential-sequel-ideas/|title= Downton Abbey team says they already have ideas for a potential sequel|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last1=Lee Lenker|first1=Maureen|date=24 September 2019|accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|first=Jessica|last=Fellowes|title=A Year in the Life of Downton Abbey: Seasonal Celebrations, Traditions, and Recipes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=esZzAwAAQBAJ|date=2014|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-1-4668-7221-9|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first=Jessica|last=Fellowes|title=Downton Abbey - A Celebration: The Official Companion to All Six Seasons|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AJUzCgAAQBAJ|date=2015|publisher=St. Martin's Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-250-09156-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first1=Jessica|last=Fellowes|first2=Matthew|last2=Sturgis|title=The Chronicles of Downton Abbey: A New Era|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TJyg0RN-ue8C&pg=PA99|date=13 November 2012|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-1-250-02762-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first=Jessica|last=Fellowes|title=The World of Downton Abbey|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NHbTXPpgRyAC&pg=PT13|date=2011|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-1-250-01620-1|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.focusfeatures.com/downton-abbey}}\n*{{IMDb title|tt6398184}}\n{{Downton Abbey}}\n{{Julian Fellowes}}{{Michael Engler}}\n{{George V}}\n[[Category:Downton Abbey]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British drama films]]\n[[Category:British historical films]]\n[[Category:Films based on television series]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Focus Features films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1927]]\n[[Category:Films set in England]]\n[[Category:Films set in country houses]]\n[[Category:Films about social class]]\n[[Category:Domestic workers in films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of George V]]\n[[Category:British LGBT-related films]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSoundtrack:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedi